ugh the eyes of those who lived it. The facts brought forth in this book are supported by case files recorded by Jewish social service workers, letters and minutes from agency meetings, oral testimonies, and much more. Cohen explores how the Truman Directive allowed the American Jewish community to handle the financial and legal responsibility for survivors, and shows what assistance the community offered the refugees and what help was not available. She investigates the particularly difficult issues that orphan children and Orthodox Jews faced, and examines the subtleties of the resettlement process in New York and other locales. Cohen uncovers the truth of survivors' early years in America and reveals the complexity of their lives as "New Americans."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHolocaust survivorsxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aHolocaust survivorszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantsxHistoirex20e sièclexÉtats-UnisxUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewish refugeesxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aJewish refugeeszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewsxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aJewszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJews, EuropeanxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aJews, EuropeanzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJuifs européensxHistoirex20e sièclexÉtats-Unis. 0aJuifsxHistoirex20e sièclexÉtats-Unis. 0aRéfugiés juifsxHistoirex20e sièclexÉtats-Unis. 0aSurvivants de l'HolocaustexHistoirex20e sièclexÉtats-Unis. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354130340uhtt